Task Requirements:

Create an S3 bucket named nautilus-web-798.
Configure the S3 bucket for static website hosting with index.html as the index document.
Allow public access to the bucket so that the website is publicly accessible.
Upload the index.html file from the /root/ directory of the AWS client host to the S3 bucket.
Verify that the website is accessible directly through the S3 website URL.



Step 1: Create the S3 Bucket
AWS Console Method:
Login to the AWS Management Console.
Navigate to S3 → Buckets → Create bucket.
Configure:
Bucket name: nautilus-web-798
Region: Choose your preferred region
Leave other options as default for now
Click Create bucket.
AWS CLI Method:
aws s3api create-bucket \
    --bucket nautilus-web-798 \
    --region us-east-1 \
    --create-bucket-configuration LocationConstraint=us-east-1
Adjust the region if you’re using a different one.
Step 2: Enable Static Website Hosting
AWS Console Method:
Go to the bucket Properties → Static website hosting.
Select Enable.
Index document: index.html
Click Save.
AWS CLI Method:
aws s3 website s3://nautilus-web-798/ --index-document index.html
Step 3: Configure Public Access
Important: To make the website publicly accessible, the bucket must allow public access.
Go to Permissions → Bucket Policy in the S3 console.
Add the following policy to allow public read:
{
    "Version": "2012-10-17",
    "Statement": [
        {
            "Sid": "PublicReadGetObject",
            "Effect": "Allow",
            "Principal": "*",
            "Action": "s3:GetObject",
            "Resource": "arn:aws:s3:::nautilus-web-798/*"
        }
    ]
}
Click Save.
AWS CLI Method:
aws s3api put-bucket-policy \
    --bucket nautilus-web-798 \
    --policy '{
        "Version":"2012-10-17",
        "Statement":[
            {
                "Sid":"PublicReadGetObject",
                "Effect":"Allow",
                "Principal":"*",
                "Action":["s3:GetObject"],
                "Resource":["arn:aws:s3:::nautilus-web-798/*"]
            }
        ]
    }'
Step 4: Upload the index.html File
AWS Console Method:
Open the bucket nautilus-web-798.
Click Upload → Add files.
Select /root/index.html from the AWS client host.
Click Upload.
AWS CLI Method:
aws s3 cp /root/index.html s3://nautilus-web-798/index.html
Step 5: Verify the Website
Go to Properties → Static website hosting in the bucket.
Copy the Endpoint URL (S3 website URL). Example:
http://nautilus-web-798.s3-website-us-east-1.amazonaws.com
Open the URL in a browser.
You should see the content of your index.html file, confirming the website is publicly accessible.
